## Question 5 — Arrhenius Equation

### Calculate the Arrhenius constant, A (4 marks)

$k = 3.46 \times 10^{-8} \text{ s}^{-1}$ at 25 °C. $E_a = 96.2 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}$.

> **Mark Scheme:**
> * **M1:** Convert T to Kelvin ($298 \text{ K}$) and $E_a$ to Joules ($96200 \text{ J mol}^{-1}$)
> * **M2:** Rearrange equation: $A = \frac{k}{e^{-E_a/RT}}$
> * **M3:** $A = \frac{3.46 \times 10^{-8}}{e^{-96200 / (8.31 \times 298)}} = \text{2.52} \times 10^9$
> * **M4:** Units: $\text{s}^{-1}$
> 
> 

